    <problem>
        <title>(Problem 1)</title>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                For each of the following sequences explain and demonstrate how to determine if they are monotonic, bounded, and whether they converge; if they converge, explain and demonstrate how to find their limit.
            </p>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>a_n=\frac{n+(-1)^n}{n}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>a_n=(-1)^n(1-\frac{1}{n})</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>a_n=\frac{n!}{n^n}</m> where <m>n!=n\cdot(n-1)\cdots\cdot 2\cdot 1</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        </introduction>
        <solution>
            <task>
                <p>
                    Here, we start by re-writing <m>a_n=1+\frac{(-1)^n}{n}</m>. 
                    Then, if we calculate and simplify <m>a_{n+1}-a_n</m>, we get:
                    <me>
                        a_{n+1}-a_n=\frac{(-1)^{n+1}}{n(n+1)}(2n+1).
                    </me>
                    This expression is sometimes positive and sometimes negative, so the sequence <m>\{a_n\}</m> is not monotonic.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Since <m>-1\leq \frac{(-1)^n}{n}\leq 1</m>, it follows that <m>0\leq 1+\frac{(-1)^n}{n}\leq 2</m>, so <m>\{a_n\}</m> is bounded.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Since <m>\lim_{n\to\infty}\frac{(-1)^n}{n}=0</m>, it follows that <m>a_n</m> converges to <m>1</m>.
                </p>
            </task>
            <task>
                <p>
                    This time, when we compute <m>a_{n+1}-a_n</m> we get:
                    <me>
                        a_{n+1}-a_n=\frac{(-1)^{n+1}}{n(n+1)}(2n^2-1).
                    </me>
                    Like above, this is sometimes positive and sometimes negative, so the sequence is not monotonic. 
                </p>
                <p>
                    Since <m>|a_n|=1-\frac{1}{n}\leq 1</m>, it follows that the sequence is bounded. 
                </p>
                <p>
                    As <m>n\to \infty</m>, the factor <m>1-\frac{1}{n}\to 1</m>. 
                    Given this, <m>a_n</m> itself will osscilate close to <m>\pm 1</m> and the limit does not exist. 
                </p>
            </task>
            <task>
                <p>
                    This time
                    <me>
                        a_{n+1}-a_n=\frac{n!}{n^n(n+1)^n}(n^n-(n+1)^n)&lt; 0
                    </me>
                    is always negative, so <m>\{a_n\}</m> is monotonic decreasing. 
                </p>
                <p>
                    Notice that 
                    <me>
                        a_n=\frac{n\cdot(n-1)\cdots(2)\cdot(1)}{n\cdot n\cdots n\cdot n}
                    </me>
                    Since <m>\frac{k}{n}\leq 1</m> for each <m>k\leq n</m>, it follows that
                    <me>
                        0\leq a_n\leq \frac{1}{n}\leq 1
                    </me>
                    and that <m>\{a_n\}</m> is bounded. 
                </p>
                <p>
                    Lastly, since we observed that <m>0\leq a_n\leq \frac{1}{n}</m> holds for every <m>n</m> and we know <m>\frac{1}{n}\to 0</m>, it follows that <m>a_n\to 0</m> as well.
                </p>
            </task>
        </solution>
    </problem>

    <problem>
        <title>(Problem 2)</title>
        <introduction>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Explain and demonstrate how to express <m>3.12\overline{5}=3.12555555\cdots</m> as a fraction of two integers by first interpreting this expression as an infinite series, and then applying results from class as appropriate.
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        Explain and demonstrate how to express <m>4.\overline{23}=4.23232323\cdots</m> as a fraction of two integers by first interpreting this expression as an infinite series, and then applying results from class as appropriate..
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
        </introduction>    
        <solution>
            <task>
                <p>
                    The key observation is that 
                    <me>
                        3.12\overline{5}=3.12+\frac{5}{10^3}+\frac{5}{10^4}+\frac{5}{10^5}+\cdots=\frac{312}{100}+\frac{5}{10^3}+\frac{5}{10^4}+\frac{5}{10^5}+\cdots
                    </me>
                    The sum <m>\frac{5}{10^3}+\frac{5}{10^4}+\frac{5}{10^5}+\cdots</m> is geometric with initial term <m>a=\frac{5}{10^3}</m> and common ratio <m>r=\frac{1}{10}</m>.
                    Using results from class, we know that this geometric sum is equal to 
                    <me>
                        \frac{a}{1-r}=\frac{5}{900}.
                    </me>
                    Adding to this <m>\frac{312}{100}</m>, we get <m>3.12\overline{5}=\frac{2813}{900}</m>.
                </p>
            </task>
            <task>
                <p>
                    Likewise, the number <m>4.\overline{23}</m> is equal to <m>4</m> plus a geometric series with initial term <m>a=\frac{23}{100}</m> and ratio <m>r=\frac{1}{100}</m>. 
                    It is therefore equal to
                    <me>
                        4+\frac{a}{1-r}=4+\frac{23}{99}=\frac{419}{99}.
                    </me>
                    
                </p>
            </task>
        </solution>
    </problem>

    <problem>
        <title>(Problem 3)</title>
        <introduction>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    For each of the following, explain and demonstrate how to find the values of <m>x</m> for which the given series converge; explain and demonstrate how to find the sum of the series (as a function of <m>x</m>) for those values of <m>x</m>. 
                </p>
            </statement>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\sum_{n=0}^\infty (-1)^nx^{-2n}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\sum_{n=0}^\infty \left(-\frac{1}{2}\right)^n(x-3)^n</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <m>\sum_{n=0}^\infty (\ln{x})^n</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        </introduction>
        <solution>
            <task>
                <p>
                    This sum is geometric with initial term <m>a=1</m> and ratio <m>r=-\frac{1}{x}^2</m>. 
                    Therefore, it converges to 
                    <me>
                        \frac{a}{1-r}=\frac{x^2}{x^2+1}
                    </me>
                    whenever <m>|-\frac{1}{x^2}|&lt; 1</m>; this happens when <m>x</m> lives in <m>(-\infty,-1)\cup (1,\infty)</m>.
                    
                </p>
            </task>
            <task>
                <p>
                    This series is geometric with initial term <m>a=1</m> and ratio <m>r=\frac{3-x}{2}</m>. 
                    Therefore, it converges to:
                    <me>
                        \frac{a}{1-r}=\frac{2}{x-1}
                    </me>
                    whenever <m>|\frac{3-x}{2}|&lt;1</m>, or <m>1&lt; x&lt; 5</m>.
                </p>
            </task>
            <task>
                <p>
                    This series is geometric with initial term <m>a=1</m> and ratio <m>r=\ln(x)</m>. 
                    Therefore, it converges to:
                    <me>
                        \frac{a}{1-r}=\frac{1}{1-\ln(x)}
                    </me>
                    whenever <m>|\ln(x)|&lt;1</m>, or <m>\frac{1}{e}&lt; x&lt; e</m>.
                </p>
            </task>
        </solution>
    </problem>

    <problem>
        <title>(Problem 4)</title>
        <introduction>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    In this problem, you will prove that the harmonic series diverges using the definitions of partial sums instead of relying on the integral test. 
                    Recall that the harmonic series is the series <m>\sum_{n=1}^\infty\frac{1}{n}</m>.
                    Let <m>S_k</m> denote its <m>k</m>-th partial sum:
                    <me>S_k=\sum_{n=1}^k\frac{1}{n}=1+\frac{1}{2}+\cdots+\frac{1}{k}.</me>
                </p>
            </statement>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Explain and demonstrate why the sequence <m>\{S_k\}</m> is monotonically increasing.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    In class, we showed that <m>S_4\geq S_2+\frac{1}{2}</m> and that <m>S_8\geq S_4+\frac{1}{2}</m>.
                    Explain and demonstrate why the inequalities 
                    <me>S_{2^n}\geq S_{2^{n-1}}+\frac{1}{2}\geq 1+\frac{n}{2}</me>
                    hold for all <m>n\geq 2</m>.
                    Conclude that the sequence of partial sums <m>S_{2^n}</m> is unbounded hence must diverge.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </introduction>
        <solution>
            <task>
                <p>
                    Answers may vary. One approach is to note that <m>S_{k}=S_{k-1}+\frac{1}{k}</m>. 
                    So, at each step, <m>S_k</m> is obtained by adding the positive number <m>\frac{1}{k}</m> to the number <m>S_{k-1}</m> which increases the sum. 
                </p>
                <p>
                    Alternatively, <m>S_{k}-S_{k-1}=\frac{1}{k}&gt; 0</m> for each <m>k</m>, which shows the sequence is increasing. 
                </p>
            </task>
            <task>
                <p>
                    First, note that
                    <me>
                        S_{2^n}=S_{2^{n-1}}+\frac{1}{2^{n-1}+1}+\frac{1}{2^{n-1}+2}+\cdots+\frac{1}{2^n}.
                    </me>
                    Of the numbers <m>\frac{1}{2^{n-1}+1},\frac{1}{2^{n-1}+2},\cdots,\frac{1}{2^n}</m>, the smallest is <m>\frac{1}{2^n}</m>. 
                    By counting carefully, the sum
                    <me>
                        \frac{1}{2^{n-1}+1}+\frac{1}{2^{n-1}+2}+\cdots+\frac{1}{2^n}
                    </me>
                    has <m>2^n-2^{n-1}=2^{n-1}(2-1)=2^{n-1}</m> terms. 
                    It follows, then, that
                    <me>
                        \frac{1}{2^{n-1}+1}+\frac{1}{2^{n-1}+2}+\cdots+\frac{1}{2^n}\geq \frac{1}{2^n}+\cdots+\frac{1}{2^n}=\frac{2^{n-1}}{2^n}=\frac{1}{2}.
                    </me>
                    This shows that <m>S_{2^n}\geq S_{2^{n-1}}+\frac{1}{2}</m>. 
                    
                </p>
                <p>
                    If we repeat this <m>n</m> times, we get
                    <me>
                        S_{2^{n-1}}+\frac{1}{2}\geq S_{2^{n-2}}+\frac{2}{2}\geq\cdots\geq S_{2^0}+\frac{n}{2}=1+\frac{n}{2}.
                    </me>
                    Since <m>\lim_{n\to\infty}1+\frac{n}{2}=\infty</m>, it follows that partial sums are unbounded from below. 
                </p>
            </task>
        </solution>
    </problem>

    <problem>
        <title>Practice: Do Not Turn In</title>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                Suppose that <m>y=f(x)</m> is some continuous, strictly increasing function defined on an interval <m>[a,b]</m>.
                These assumptions guarantee that <m>f(x)</m> is an invertible function, so we will let <m>x=g(y)</m>, defined on the interval <m>[f(a),f(b)]</m> denote this inverse function.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Explain why the following equation of integrals is true without doing any calculations:
                    <me>\int_{f\left(a\right)}^{f\left(b\right)}\pi\left[b^2-g\left(y\right)^2\right]dy=\int_a^b2\pi x\left[f\left(x\right)-f\left(a\right)\right]dx</me>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Use a combination of our integration strategies to provide a second explanation for why this equation is true. 
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
    </problem>
    <hint>
        <p>
            You may find drawing a picture helpful for organizing your thoughts.
        </p>
    </hint>
